## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task M-2 requires ongoing assessment of security controls to determine whether controls continue to be implemented correctly, operating as intended, and producing the desired outcomes with respect to meeting security requirements. The ongoing assessment program is defined in the continuous monitoring strategy (Day 52) and executed throughout the authorization period. Today I work through the M-2 assessment activities for the OpenMRS system — organizing them by assessment type, documenting the specific procedures for each, and thinking about how assessment findings feed back into the SSP and POA&M.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The distinction that crystallized Task M-2 for me today is the difference between a control being *present* and a control being *effective*.

Every control in the OpenMRS SSP was assessed during the Task A-3 formal assessment. The assessor verified that each control was present — configured, documented, and operating at the time of assessment. The SAR reflected the point-in-time state of controls as of the assessment dates.

Six months from now, each of those controls may still be present in the sense that the configuration exists — but some may no longer be effective in the sense that they produce the desired security outcome. The CloudWatch metric filter for failed authentication anomalies may still be configured but may have a threshold that is now calibrated incorrectly because the user population grew and the baseline changed. The quarterly access review may still be occurring but may have shifted from a genuine recertification exercise to a rubber-stamp approval because the Health IT Manager is overwhelmed with other priorities. The session timeout may still be configured at 15 minutes but may have been temporarily adjusted to 60 minutes to accommodate a clinical workflow need and never reverted.

None of these degradations would be captured by monitoring for configuration changes. They require periodic effectiveness verification — actually testing whether the control produces the expected outcome in the current environment.

This is the core value of Task M-2: it catches the difference between a control that is formally in place and a control that is genuinely working.

