## Assessment Findings and the Feedback Loop

Every M-2 assessment produces one of three outcomes:

*No findings:* Controls are operating as intended. Document in monitoring log. No SSP update required.

*Minor finding (process improvement):* A control is operating but with suboptimal effectiveness — a backup took 15 minutes longer than expected, an access review missed one account before the ISSO caught it in the completeness check. Document in monitoring log with corrective action taken. No POA&M entry unless the finding recurs.

*Substantive finding (control degradation):* A control is not operating as intended or is producing inadequate results — a backup restoration failed the verification checklist, a vulnerability scan found a High finding that has been present for 45 days without a POA&M entry, an access review revealed a role assignment that has been incorrect for multiple quarters. These findings require: monitoring log documentation; SSP update if the implementation description needs correction; POA&M entry if the remediation will take longer than 30 days; and AO notification per Condition 3 if the finding materially affects the authorization basis.

The feedback loop from M-2 findings to SSP and POA&M updates is what keeps the authorization package current — not just at re-authorization, but throughout the authorization period.

