## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The rubber-stamp access review concern — effectiveness degradation not through misconfiguration but through process habituation — was directly informed by the circumstances of the **2013 Target breach**, which had a vendor access control dimension that is less discussed than the malware component.

Target's HVAC vendor, Fazio Mechanical, had network credentials for the Target environment that were being used for electronic billing and project management. The credentials were compromised and used as the initial entry point for the attackers who eventually reached Target's payment systems.

Post-breach analysis found that Target's access review processes for vendor accounts were not regularly verifying whether the access scope was still appropriate — the Fazio account had more network access than the HVAC billing function required, and that scope had not been reviewed and challenged in the way it would have been if the access review process was genuinely evaluating role accuracy rather than just confirming account continuation.

This connects directly to the Finding A-5 remediation — updating the access review template to prompt role accuracy evaluation rather than just account continuation. The Target vendor account breach illustrates what happens when access reviews confirm that accounts exist without confirming that access scopes are still appropriate.

An access review that asks "Does Fazio still have an HVAC contract with us?" and stops there misses the question "Is Fazio's network access scope still limited to what their HVAC billing function requires?" The updated MyClinic access review template — which now asks about role accuracy, not just access continuation — is a small but meaningful process change that the Target breach illustrates the importance of.

