## What I Am Still Thinking About

One open question from the quarterly access review procedure: what is the right threshold for flagging a dormant account?

I set 60 days of inactivity as the threshold for Health IT Manager review. But for a clinical system, 60 days of inactivity might be entirely legitimate — a clinician on extended medical leave, a part-time physician who works once monthly, a staff member on parental leave. Flagging all of these for deactivation review would generate significant administrative burden and potentially disrupt legitimate clinical relationships.

The 60-day threshold might benefit from being role-differentiated: IT Administrator and ISSO accounts with 30 days of inactivity should be immediately flagged — there is no operational reason for a privileged account to be inactive for 30 days. Clinical accounts with 90 days of inactivity should be flagged, but with a specific question to the Health IT Manager: "Is this person on approved leave and expected to return?" rather than "Should this account be deactivated?" Administrative staff accounts with 60 days of inactivity should be flagged with a standard review.

Role-differentiated dormancy thresholds make the access review more operationally realistic and more effective — higher scrutiny where the privilege level warrants it, more flexibility where the operational context supports it.

I want to update the quarterly review template to reflect this differentiated threshold before the next quarterly review cycle.

